<@U9N0B9JFR> There hasn't been tons, but these articles might (partially) answer your question.  Both compare students using a M&I treatment to a traditional treatment in intro mechanics <https://journals.aps.org/prper/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevSTPER.10.020125> and intro E&M <https://journals.aps.org/prper/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevSTPER.5.020105> <@U1YCYCK61> can definitely give you more context.

<@UBN8AAZS7> It may have been posted somewhere already, but the AAPT came out with a set of recommendations for computational physics at the undergrad level. To specifically answer your question, check out Appendix B. I don't think there's anything like that for computational physics-integrated courses just because there is no standard canon of "stuff you're supposed to teach" yet, unlike in a conventional Uni Physics I class. It's up to us to help figure out what that canon ought to be.

That, really, is the thing that needs to be figured out for curricular integration to become more widespread.
